d by nutritional status","Ghrelin suppresses appetite"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGhrelin activates hypothalamic arcuate nucleus neurons containing neuropeptide Y\u003C/strong\u003E, which are involved in stimulating appetite. Ghrelin is known as the \u0027hunger hormone\u0027 for its role in meal initiation by increasing appetite. It is primarily produced in the stomach and its levels rise before meals, signalling hunger, and fall after eating.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGhrelin levels decrease before meals\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Ghrelin levels increase before meals, promoting the sensation of hunger.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGhrelin is produced primarily in the pancreas\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While ghrelin can be found in small amounts in the pancreas, it is primarily produced in the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGhrelin levels are unaffected by nutritional status\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Ghrelin levels are affected by nutritional status, as they rise in response to fasting and decrease after food intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGhrelin suppresses appetite\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Ghrelin stimulates appetite, making it a key hormone in the regulation of hunger and energy balance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ghrelin is a hormone that stimulates appetite by activating neurons in the hypothalamus.","Ghrelin levels increase before meals and decrease after eating, demonstrating its role in appetite.","Ghrelin is produced primarily in the stomach and responds to changes in nutritional status."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020 Oct 8;64(4):607-647. 